---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="Architecture" description="System topology for the SuperFIB and Stokvel Society case studies.">
  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container page-hero-layout">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div class="page-intro">Architecture</div>
        <h1 class="page-title">Topology over theater.</h1>
        <p class="page-copy">
          I use diagrams to explain where authority lives, how state moves, and what the system has to keep in sync. I do not use them to leak implementation details that should stay private.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="manifest">
        <div class="manifest-row">
          <strong>What these diagrams show</strong>
          <p>Systems, handoff points, and the direction of trust.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="manifest-row">
          <strong>What they do not show</strong>
          <p>Trading logic, thresholds, or any implementation detail that would expose sensitive behavior.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="container feature-stack">
      <article class="project-entry">
        <div class="detail-header stack-lg">
          <div class="eyeline">SuperFIB</div>
          <h2 class="detail-title">Hub-and-spoke control across trading surfaces</h2>
          <p class="panel-copy">
            The backend API is the authority. The indicator, execution layer, and dashboard are coordinated around it so parity can be checked and stale state can be caught early.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-panel">
          <div class="diagram-frame">
            <img src="/images/diagram-system/superfib.svg" alt="Flow diagram showing Pine Script, a WordPress API as source of truth, MT5 expert advisors, and a React dashboard." />
          </div>
          <p class="diagram-caption">The point of the shape is control. One authoritative state reduces ambiguity when multiple runtimes need to agree.</p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="project-entry">
        <div class="detail-header stack-lg">
          <div class="eyeline">Stokvel Society</div>
          <h2 class="detail-title">A clear finance flow for contributions and payouts</h2>
          <p class="panel-copy">
            This system is intentionally simpler in shape. The important thing is that money movement stays understandable and every step can be explained to a member or administrator.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-panel">
          <div class="diagram-frame">
            <img src="/images/diagram-system/stokvel-society.svg" alt="Linear flow diagram showing member contributions moving into a ledger or trust layer and then into payouts." />
          </div>
          <p class="diagram-caption">The diagram focuses on readability because the product itself depends on trust and clarity more than visual complexity.</p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
